diff:1617427333:1615639923:=59,71c59%0a%3c #foxbegin 210403-052213-155420#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Hoocąk reclamation efforts  %0a%3c -> - roochis%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c With about 50 speakers spread throughout the northern United States and Canada, Hoocąk is an extremely endangered language. Kirsten Betancurt, a member of the Hoocąk, believes the extinction of the language will lead to the extinction of the culture. She has quit her job in order to be a Language Apprentice. The Language Apprenticeship program is a special reclamation program started by and for the Hoocąk community. Through this program, apprentices are paired with a speaker, who they spend up to two years with (every weekday, seven hours a day) learning the language. After they complete their Apprenticeship, they become a Hoocąk instructor for children attending Hoocąk High Schools and other adults. Betancurt characterized this Language Apprenticeship program as the bridge between the  elder Hoocąk community, who learned Hoocąk as a first language, and younger generations. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.neh.gov/article/reviving-ho-chunk%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210403-052213-155420#%0a---%0a> %0a
